		 	<span id="comment_score_64411796" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64411796); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Informative)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~beelsebob">beelsebob</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~beelsebob">( 529313 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64411796">		
		on Sunday April 21, 2024 @08:18AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23297100&amp;cid=64411796">#64411796</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64411796"><p>No - that&#226;(TM)s the universe expanding at a constant rate.  If you stretch a sheet evenly all over, and then observe from a particular point on that sheet, you&#226;(TM)ll see the relative expansion being faster the further things are from you.  What&#226;(TM)s being proposed here is that the cosmological constant can vary both in terms of time and space.</p></div>
	</div>

