<div id="comment_status_64412354" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64412354" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64412354" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64412354" name="comment_link_64412354" href="//science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23297100&amp;cid=64412354" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64412354)" >Rotating Universe [Re:My hypothesis is]</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64412354" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64412354); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>2</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Geoffrey.landis">Geoffrey.landis</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Geoffrey.landis">( 926948 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64412354"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64412354"><p><div class="quote"><p>The universe doesn't rotate because there is no reference frame for it to rotate in, if there were then the universe wouldn't be the universe.</p></div><p>In General Relativity, rotation is not relative.  You can tell if you're rotating without reference to the outside universe, and in fact G&#246;del showed <a href="http://journals.aps.org/rmp/abstract/10.1103/RevModPhys.21.447" title="aps.org">a solution to the Einstein field equations</a> [aps.org] for the case of a rotating universe (...and the solution was pretty <a href="https://www.space.com/rotating-universe-would-permit-time-travel#" title="space.com">weird</a> [space.com]).</p><p>But, sufficiently precise astronomical measurements have looked for whether the universe is rotating, and it turns out it isn't.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64412354">

