		<div id="comment_body_64412938"><p><div class="quote"><p>you are arguing against a point that wasn't made.</p></div><p>
The point _was_ made: "constant rate" means that the rate of expansion remains the same with time. What you are talking about is a _common_ rate of expansion. The summary says that they are considering variations in the rate as a function of position but, by saying that the rate is constant that inplies that it does not vary with time and that is wrong: we know from multiple supernova studies that the expansion is accelerating. This even gave is a new possible "end of the universe" scenario: the "big rip"<span class="substr"> </span></p></div>
	</div>

